bikersharing-demand

Zhaohui Zhu

2019/12/1

Bike sharing systems are a means of renting bicycles where the process of obtaining membership, rental, and bike return is automated via a network of kiosk locations throughout a city. Using these systems, people are able rent a bike from a one location and return it to a different place on an as-needed basis. Currently, there are over 500 bike-sharing programs around the world.

The data generated by these systems makes them attractive for researchers because the duration of travel, departure location, arrival location, and time elapsed is explicitly recorded. Bike sharing systems therefore function as a sensor network, which can be used for studying mobility in a city

This dataset contains 12 Variables.

  • datetime - hourly date + timestamp

  • season - 1 = spring, 2 = summer, 3 = fall, 4 = winter

  • holiday - whether the day is considered a holiday

  • workingday - whether the day is neither a weekend nor holiday

  • weather

  • 1: Clear, Few clouds, Partly cloudy, Partly cloudy

  • 2: Mist + Cloudy, Mist + Broken clouds, Mist + Few clouds, Mist

  • 3: Light Snow, Light Rain + Thunderstorm + Scattered clouds, Light Rain + Scattered clouds

  • 4: Heavy Rain + Ice Pallets + Thunderstorm + Mist, Snow + Fog

  • temp - temperature in Celsius

  • atemp - ‘Feels like’ temperature in Celsius

  • humidity - relative humidity

  • windspeed - wind speed

  • casual - number of non-registered user rentals initiated

  • registered - number of registered user rentals initiated

  • count - number of total rentals

It can be seen from the figure that season, weather, temp, atemp and humidity are related to count Other variables are not strongly correlated with count.

ggplot(data = data_bikeshare, aes(temp,count)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.3, aes(color = temp)) +
  xlab("temperature in Celsius") +
  ylab("number of total rentals")

The scatter plot above shows that as the temperature rises, the amount of total rent also increases.

pl <- ggplot(data_bikeshare,
             aes(datetime,count)) +
  geom_point(aes(color=temp),alpha=0.5)
pl + scale_color_continuous(low = '#55D8CE',high = '#FF6E2E') +
  ylab("number of total rentals")

There is a clear seasonal trend. The total number of bicycles rented in winter seems to decrease, while the total number of bicycles rented in summer seems to increase. In addition, the number of rental bicycles has increased from 2011 to 2013.

Build the model

data_bikeshare_mat_x %<>% as_tibble %>% dplyr::select(season3,  
                                                      season4,   
                                                      weather2,  
                                                      temp,  
                                                      atemp, 
                                                      humidity,
                                                      windspeed)  

data_bikeshare_lm <- cbind(data_bikeshare_mat_x,count = data_bikeshare_mat_y) %>% as.data.frame()


lm.fit <- lm(count~.-atemp,data = data_bikeshare_lm)

The constant variance assumption hold. The normality assumption hold. Since the observed values 9321, 8529, 9480 are leverage points, they need to be deleted.

Conclusion

As can be seen from the final fit, seasonal factors have the greatest impact on the variable count, and weather and temperature also have a large effect on the total rent. This is also consistent with the assumption I made before. The impact of windspeed on count is small, but it is still significant, which is a factor to be considered in predicting the total rent.

This article focuses on the prediction problem and observes the prediction performance of the OLS model.The ME and MPE are -0.339614 and 4.832725 respectively, so the OLS model has a good prediction result. , But the RMSE result is large, indicating that the residual contains information that is not mined.

I believe this model can help bike sharing companies develop some business strategies.For example, different rents in different weather and seasons
